UNIVERSITY OF CONPCECION

"Cyborg Beast" is a prosthetic hand developed by Jorge Zúñiga, Ivan Owen and Peter Binkley.
In order to adapt this hand to be used for cycling, which is a frequent requirement in children, the Laboratory of 3D Innovation of the Center for Advanced Prosthodontics and Implant Dentistry of the University of Concepción, made changes to the original design for this purpose.
The original design was modified by adding a rigid palm, composed of an arch which generates a concavity (FIG 1 and 1) which adapts to the handle of the bicycle. This arch of 35.8 mm length is inclined in 21.65 degrees to the front side in order to apply the required load to control the bicycle. Also, this allows an adequate distribution of the possible impacts received without the need of closing the hand.

The angle of the thumb was modified so that at the moment of action of the prosthetic, the index finger would join the thumb and form the posture of "clamp" to be able to hold the handlebar. (FIG 1.5 and details) This modification was developed by biomedical engineers of the University of Concepción.

Two removable housings were designed to add a super hero motif to the prosthetic hand. These pieces also play a role of protecting the mechanism of strings and elastics. Both housings are attached to the prosthesis by velcro strips to facilitate the maintenance of the mechanism. (FIG 1.5 and 2).
This prosthesis was designed to allow children with congenital anomalies of the hand, have lost part of it or those who maintain the integrated structure of the wrist to drive a bicycle.
Improvements:

  1. Concave palm that adapts to the bicycle handlebars.
  2. Structure of rigid palm with volumes which allow the transmission of loads avoiding risks of injuries and allowing greater stability.
  3. This design allows good control of the bicycle while driving in straight line and turns.
  4. Removable housing for protection of tensioners with motifs of super heroes.
  5. The thumb joins the index finger changing the angle allowing to hold the handle of a bicycle.
    Requirements:
    These pieces were made with Stratasys ABSplus manufactured in a Stratasys Uprintplus 3D printer which have a resistance of 40% higher than the normal ABS of the same brand. If other materials are used, mechanical resistance should be compared to maintain the design with a minimum of security.
    For safety recommendations: See the Manual of Cyborg Beast, section “General Recommendations for e--‐NABLE Prosthetic Devices”.

The bottom Twiggy drive in the Lisa 1, and the single floppy slot on the Lisa 2 also has a mounting point for an SD card reader, or extension cable such as this one:

http://www.amazon.com/Manufacture-Sdhc-micro-Reader-Extension-Cable/dp/B0085GGO92

The parts of the case are 6 separate pieces that should snap together, though a small amount of glue at the corners will ensure that the model holds together during handling.

title: Ball_Foot for D-Bot
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The original is a great idea and a beautiful design.
However, last time I looked before today, parksddd proposed to replace the corner plates with it.
For me that was a step too far, I did prefer metal plates and these can be mounted with more force then I would dare to use with these printed ones.
So I decided to work around those plates.

Big disadvantage, compared to the original: these have to be printed with print supports.
I did that with Slic3r (in PLA) and that makes for a lot of cleaning up to do afterwards.
And not a very nice surface on the supported plane, but that is not visible when mounted.

I use cheap, much softer balls, hoping for even better damping. Available in toy shops and such.

Update (2017-08-23): In practice they worked excellent, a bit too good even, because the whole structure was swaying.
At first I thought that didn't matter, as long as the structure is reasonable stiff, but now I have direct extrusion with 2 motors on top of the X-carriage, I feel that one shouldn't challenge eventual play in the axes too much with all that mass, so for the moment I substituted them for the original stiff little rubber feet.
There is not too much of a noise to damp anyway at the moment, but as soon as I tire of it I shall try to replace the soft balls with tennis balls, which should give much less sway.
Just as parksddd in the original design meant. ;-)
Edit (9/14/17): they are back on, nice and quiet does it and I now print with low velocities anyway.

description.text: This is redesigned version hot end to replace the fault prone UM hot end.  It is designed to bolt on to an otherwise standard assembly.  A lathe and drill press are necessary to machine the parts.  This design offers a single improved connection between the bowden tube and nozzle to eliminate leaks and plugs.  The nozzle is designed for quick change-over.

I have been working on a solution to the common hot end problems with the Ultimaker. I have been hesitant to show my work because I wanted to prove its effectiveness. I now have about 30 hours of printing with good success. More testing is in order. Some features to the design: -M7 thread on the bowden tube
-New peek block with M7 thread through and chamfer on bottom side to effect 'flare' connection with nozzle
-New heater block accepts standard heater and thermistor. Longer body for more thread engagement. Turned down to reduce heated mass.
-New nozzle with male flare compresses end of bowden tube against PEEK.
-As tested has .4mm tip. Some pros: -Less connections for possible leaks. The bowden tube has a flare connection directly to the nozzle.
-Quick nozzle change-over
-Insulator is still PEEK
-Mounts in standard wood block (part 10b?) with white/blue clip. I think the clip is now unnecessary though.
-Same stack-up height as original equipment so 'z' switch can stay in same range
-Stable temperture with standard Marlin PID settings
-No PTFE tape
-Nozzle bore has 60 deg included bottom for better flow (hopefully) Cons: -Lathe and Drill press needed to make new parts. Last 2 pics show nozzle after printing for inspection. Filament pulled back while hot. Dis-assembled while cold. One shot looking up bowden tube for plugs. Last shot of flare side of nozzle. The PLA attached to the nozzle was not a 'plug', but did need to be twisted free of bowden tube. As most people don't have access to the tools necessary to make this thing, I am considering offering this as a kit if further testing proves reliability and sufficient interest is shown. Work in progress. Looking for comments and feedback. Matt

title: Surface Pro Controller Dock for Xbox 360 Controller

description.text: Now you can play games in bed, in the bathroom (you know you would!!), on the couch, standing up, or practically ANYWHERE on your Surface Pro/Surface Pro 2! Print the dock, put it on your xbox 360 controller, and connect the controller to your Surface Pro. Play games from the Xbox Live store, from Steam, or anything else that works on your Surface Pro and is compatible with a joystick! YouTube video demo: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9whC4iE7HPs

PRINT AT YOUR OWN RISK.
BY PRINTING THIS, YOU AGREE TO NOT HOLD ME RESPONSIBLE FOR ANY DAMAGE THAT RESULTS. (for example, if it breaks apart and your surface pro falls and breaks). Play with it on a cushiony surface (such as your bed or a pillow) until you get a feel for how strong it is. Hopefully some mechanical engineers can give some tips for a more optimal design (in terms of weight and tension management).

All pieces printed on my replicator 1 dual. Suggested print settings via Makerware v2.3.1.18
Controller-Block-Top.stl and Controller-Block-Bottom.stl
+20% infill
+7 shells
+NO to raft
+YES to supports Surface-Dock-Left.stl and Surface-Dock-Right.stl
+20% infill
+7 shells
+YES to raft (if you usually experience peeling when printing)
+NO to supports (not needed even though the side edge may appear to have an overhang) Surface-Dock-Connecter [Print 3].stl
+10% infill
+3 shells
+NO to raft
+NO to supports I printed the Controller Block (Top and Bottom) using 20% infill and 7 shells with PLA. I printed the Surface Dock pieces (left and right) using 10% infill and 3 shells in my initial test, but I would recommend using the 20% infill / 7 shells as well, as I recommended above. If I make more builds, I'll update you on suggestions for even better settings. Sturdiness will depend on the infill, number of shells, and optimization of your printing environment. For example, if your build plate is not level and the plastic layers do not stack perfectly on top of each other, your build will be weaker. I did experience some points where my plastic didn't print nicely, but it still seems to hold find and is ok. I will test it out more to see how well it holds, but for now I recommend you be very careful, perhaps playing over a soft cushiony surface so that if it breaks, your Surface Pro does not. Please print 3 of the little connector pieces so that you can hammer them into the holes in the Surface Dock so you can connect the left and right sides together. Hammer may be necessary! I'd love to see your builds! Here is the Xbox 360 Wireless Controller receiver I bought:
http://www.amazon.com/Xbox-360-Wireless-Gaming-Receiver-Windows/dp/B000HZFCT2/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1387269109&sr=8-2&keywords=xbox+360+wireless+receiver Xbox 360 Wireless Controller Receiver Driver:
http://www.microsoft.com/hardware/en-us/d/xbox-360-wireless-controller-for-windows Instructions on how to install the driver on Windows 7/8 (sometimes it is confusing, even though it is a standard product):
http://forums.xbox.com/xbox_forums/xbox_support/f/7/t/1570303.aspx

description.text:
I designed this because all the ducts I had already printed kept getting knocked off. This started happening after I screwed the nozzle as far into the block as it would go to make filament loading easier. This did make loading easier, but the higher nozzle was now above the duct bottoms.

This is a low profile, cyclonic flow fan duct. I designed this to reduce warping by providing increased airflow. The nozzles are angled to produce cyclonic air flow action which actually cools a much wider area. They are also pointed downward so as to minimize nozzle cooling. I recommend this with 100% fan speed if you are having warping problems.
Your heat tube wiring must exit on the right side of the block.

Please check out my new product: The "OFFi" Auto-off switch for ANET A8 at: http://www.ebay.com/sch/i.html?_nkw=jimb15122

description.text:
I designed this Thing to make it very easy to access the extruder of the Anet a8 Printer, when it got jammed. In addition, changing the filament is super easy, because you actually can see, if the material fits the hole.
In addition to the Anet A8, I build a version for the Tronxy printer too. In this version, the 11mm of the missing heatsink are taken into account.

UPDATE: I added a version 1.1
-> use a rubber band in order to get better contact to the heatsink (many people criticized the lack of cantact)

You will need:

-1x M4 metric screw (min 20mm) and nut(s), best solution would be a wingnut
-2x M3 metric screw (min 30mm) and nuts ==> Leftover from the Printer itself!
-2x M4 metric screw (max 18mm) to fasten the whole thing on the linear bearings (remove the upper two M4x8 screws)

  • to turn the cooler 90° and fasten it with matching cutting screws on the upper side
  • to drill the existing holes up to 6mm diameter (like on the picture)
  • to fasten the extruder motor with the stock screw, which you removed, when you bulit the printer. For the other hole, just take a standard leftover screw from the printer.

Enjoy the print and please report back, how this design improved or did not improve your prints :)

Disclaimer: I am NOT responsible for any damage, you might cause (for example when drilling in the heatsink!)

The original Sketchup files are included. Be free and make some changes, if you want :)

description.text:
When I upgraded my Z axis to T8 lead screw, I couldn't still get over the wobbles on my prints. So I decided to upgrade the 8mm Z axis rods to 10mm but the design was missing in the original rsdoc files. So I redesigned the original ones to use 10mm bars on my Z axis.

You need to print both X axis motor holder and idler, Z motor mounts and top holders. Motor mounts and top holders can be mirrored when printing. Because of the thickness of 10mm bars, the nozzle tip would be positioned 2mm ahead. So you should reposition the vertical alumium extrusions 2mm back.

NOTE: Nevertheless, my wobble effect is not decreased until I switched from direct drive to bowden system. Now my wobbles are disappeared and I can print faster :)

description.text:
Updated 2/19/17

Ever like the variable designs of FlatMinis, but the customization of Dungeon Dolls? Ever wanted more options? Look no further! Inspired by the aesthetic of GrumpyRobot's FlatMinis, and DutchMogul's Dungeon Doll system, come Trixster_98's take on the classic Dungeon Doll.

This handy Bard includes a lute, plain pants, shirt with chain, a robinhood style hat, and a cape base if you wish or a plain base if not. I printed mine at 200% (Red) and the base stands at 56 mm tall. You can also print at 150% (Grey) which stands at 42 mm. Fully customizable and modular, look for more designs to come in the following weeks.

These designs are fully compatible with DutchMogul's original Dungeon Dolls, but not with FlatMinis
Made in Tinkercad, red printed at my library, grey printed on my Monoprice MP Select Mini
The remixed and improved version of my 2014 work that was unprintable and abandoned shortly after inception

Printing
The pieces should be printed at 150-200% depending on what you feel your printers accuracy to be. My printer can make all the details clearly visible at 100% but needs the print to be at 150% in order to fit together well.
The picture shows the 3 sizes of 200%, 150%, and 100%

Preparation
In order for the pieces to properly fit together, you will need to lightly sand them with a set of needle files. The heads just need very minute sanding in the eye holes. My first layer is always slightly off which always needs work in that one spot. The studs that attach to the shirt and pants need light sanding, but the holes should be fine, depending on your printers accuracy. The shirt stud typically needs a very small amount of sanding compared to the pant studs. The bottom that fits onto the base will most likely need sanding on both the hole and stud depending on accuracy.

Always test fit pieces together as you sand. I'm not responsible for ruined pieces due to too much sanding.

I designed this Thing to make it very easy to access the extruder of the Anet a8 Printer, when it got

  • to turn the cooler 90° and fasten it with matching cutting screws on the upper side
  • to drill the existing holes up to 6mm diameter (like on the picture)
  • to fasten the extruder motor with the stock screw, which you removed, when you bulit the printer.
    For the other hole, just take a standard leftover screw from the printer.
    Enjoy the print and please report back, how this design improved or did not improve your prints :)
